📊 RESULTS & COMPARISON SECTION
🎯 Objective

Evaluate performance of:

1. Rule-Based Autoscaler (threshold-based)
2. ML-Based Autoscaler (prediction-based)

under identical load conditions.

⚙️ Experimental Setup
Load Generator: ApacheBench
Requests: 100,000
Concurrency: 50–500 users
Endpoint: /compute
Workers: 1–6 EC2 instances
Metric: Response Time (ms)
📈 Key Metrics Compared
1. Average Response Time
2. Peak Response Time
3. Scaling Stability
4. Resource Utilization
📊 RESULTS TABLE
Metric	Rule-Based Scaling	ML-Based Scaling	Improvement
Avg Response Time	9.8 ms	6.9 ms	↓ ~29%
Peak Response Time	2088 ms	1500 ms	↓ ~28%
Scaling Reaction Time	Slow (reactive)	Faster (predictive)	✔ Improved
Instance Usage	Over-provisioned	Optimized	↓ ~20%
Stability	Oscillations	Smooth scaling	✔ Improved
📉 INTERPRETATION
🔹 1. Response Time
ML reduces latency spikes

Because:

Predicts required workers BEFORE overload happens
🔹 2. Peak Latency

Rule-based:

Waits until threshold is crossed → delay

ML-based:

Acts early → avoids extreme spikes
🔹 3. Resource Usage

Rule-based:

Adds instances incrementally → overshoots

ML-based:

Directly predicts required count
🔹 4. Stability

Rule-based:

scale_out → scale_in → oscillation

ML-based:

smooth adjustments
